---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const installerUrl = "https://github.com/Zwin-ux/arbitrage/releases/latest/download/market-data-recorder-setup.exe";
const portableUrl = "https://github.com/Zwin-ux/arbitrage/releases/latest/download/market-data-recorder-app-portable.zip";
const checksumsUrl = "https://github.com/Zwin-ux/arbitrage/releases/latest/download/SHA256SUMS.txt";
const sourceUrl = "https://github.com/Zwin-ux/arbitrage";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Download | Superior"
  description="Download the Superior Windows build, inspect the release artifacts, and keep paper mode active while live remains locked."
>
  <section class="page-hero compact page-hero-split">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">Release distribution</p>
      <h1>Install the Windows build. Keep paper mode active.</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Download Superior, record observed Polymarket books, inspect route deductions, and keep live execution locked until the system checks are complete. Optional Copilot model keys stay local.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="button primary" href={installerUrl}>Download installer</a>
        <a class="button secondary" href={portableUrl}>Download portable zip</a>
        <a class="button secondary" href={sourceUrl} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">View source</a>
      </div>
      <div class="badge-row" aria-label="Download highlights">
        <span class="badge">Windows-first installer</span>
        <span class="badge">No exchange account required to start</span>
        <span class="badge">Paper mode on by default</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <aside class="hero-checklist">
      <p class="eyebrow">First launch</p>
      <h2>The first run stays short and deliberate.</h2>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Create a guided profile with conservative defaults.</li>
        <li>Keep Polymarket on and leave credentials blank if recorder plus paper mode is enough for now.</li>
        <li>Add an OpenAI-compatible, Anthropic, Gemini, or Ollama model only if you want Copilot help reading routes or drafting paper bots.</li>
        <li>Store any later credentials in the OS keychain, not in JSON, DuckDB, or logs.</li>
        <li>Run the recorder first, then inspect the scanner and paper the route against local market data.</li>
        <li>If Windows SmartScreen appears, compare the download hash with the release manifest before running it.</li>
      </ul>
    </aside>
  </section>

  <section class="workflow-band">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <p class="eyebrow">Sequence</p>
      <h2>Record first. Inspect the route. Keep live locked.</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        The installer, setup flow, and Hangar all point at the same sequence: record books, inspect the route, paper it, and only then decide whether the machine has earned more trust.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="workflow-steps">
      <article>
        <span>01</span>
        <h3>Install</h3>
        <p>Use the Windows installer for shortcuts, uninstall support, and the cleanest consumer setup path.</p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <span>02</span>
        <h3>Choose safe defaults</h3>
        <p>Pick a goal, keep the Guided template, and start with the starter risk policy unless you already know the workflow.</p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <span>03</span>
        <h3>Feed the machine</h3>
        <p>Start the recorder so Scanner and paper routes work from local evidence instead of assumptions.</p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <span>04</span>
        <h3>Keep live locked</h3>
        <p>Credentials, acknowledgements, diagnostics, and paper activity must all pass before live mode becomes available.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="download-grid">
    <article class="download-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Recommended</p>
      <h2>Windows installer</h2>
      <p>
        Look for <code>market-data-recorder-setup.exe</code> in the latest GitHub release. The filename stays stable in v1 even while the public product name is Superior.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="button primary" href={installerUrl}>Download installer</a>
      </div>
      <ul class="signal-list">
        <li>Creates shortcuts and uninstall support</li>
        <li>Designed for guided onboarding and paper-first use</li>
        <li>Best choice if you want the smoothest consumer setup experience</li>
      </ul>
    </article>
    <article class="download-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Portable</p>
      <h2>Windows bundle zip</h2>
      <p>
        Look for <code>market-data-recorder-app-portable.zip</code> if you want the portable app folder instead of the installer.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="button secondary" href={portableUrl}>Download portable zip</a>
      </div>
      <ul class="signal-list">
        <li>Contains the app executable and runtime files</li>
        <li>No installer required</li>
        <li>Best for testing, demos, and isolated environments</li>
      </ul>
    </article>
    <article class="download-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Trust</p>
      <h2>Verify what you download</h2>
      <p>Superior ships unsigned in v1. Use the public release manifest and the public repo together:</p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="button secondary" href={checksumsUrl}>Download SHA256SUMS</a>
        <a class="button secondary" href={sourceUrl} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Open GitHub</a>
      </div>
      <ul class="signal-list">
        <li>Compare the installer or portable zip against <code>SHA256SUMS.txt</code></li>
        <li>Read the release notes and trust docs before you move beyond paper mode</li>
        <li>SmartScreen friction is expected until the project has signing infrastructure</li>
      </ul>
    </article>
    <article class="download-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Source build</p>
      <h2>Inspect everything before you run it</h2>
      <p>If Releases is empty, or if you want source-level visibility first, use the repo directly:</p>
      <pre><code>python -m pip install -e ".[dev]"
market-data-recorder-app</code></pre>
      <p>
        That gets you the desktop app without waiting for a packaged binary. Use this path if you want source-level visibility into storage, packaging, and live-unlock guardrails.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
